## H. Reference

### H.1 Methodology definitions

| Methodology | When to use | Example |
| --- | --- | --- |
| **Black box** | No code knowledge. Test through K8s API/CLI only. | `kubectl apply` CR → assert Deployment Ready |
| **White box** | Full code knowledge. Target specific branches. | Unit test for StatefulSet spec builder |
| **Grey box** | Partial knowledge. External interaction + internal observation. | Create CR, verify reconcile via metrics/logs |

### H.2 Scope boundary rules

- Tests MUST be relevant to the ADR/PR scope.
- Do NOT test Non-Goals unless guarding regression.
- Open questions in ADR → at least one MQE exploratory test.
- Customer risk with behavior change → at least one regression test.

### H.3 Upstream SPIRE test reference

The upstream [spiffe/spire](https://github.com/spiffe/spire) project maintains high testing standards. Use their patterns as a quality bar.

**Test directory structure** (`github.com/spiffe/spire/test/`):

| Directory | Purpose | Key patterns |
| --- | --- | --- |
| `test/testca/` | CA and certificate helpers | `testca.New(tb, td)` creates a full CA; `ca.CreateX509SVID(id)` issues SVIDs; functional options: `WithID()`, `WithLifetime()`, `WithKeyUsage()` |
| `test/testkey/` | Deterministic key generation | `testkey.NewEC256(tb)` for test keys — avoids slow key generation |
| `test/fakes/` | Mock implementations | Fake datastores, node attestors, workload attestors |
| `test/spiretest/` | Assertion and test helpers | `spiretest.AssertProtoEqual()`, log matchers, socket API helpers, temp dir management |
| `test/integration/suites/` | Suite-per-feature integration tests | Each suite has `conf/`, numbered step scripts (`01-run-server`, `02-assert-attestation`), and `teardown` |

**Quality patterns to follow:**

- **Dedicated test helper packages:** Keep test utilities in separate packages (like our `test/e2e/utils/`), not inline in test files.
- **Functional options for test objects:** SPIRE uses `WithID()`, `WithLifetime()`, `WithKeyUsage()` to customize test certificates. Our equivalent is `cspiffeIDMutator` in `SetupAttestationTest`.
- **Immediate failure on setup errors:** SPIRE uses `require.NoError(tb, err)` for setup — never ignore errors. Our equivalent: `Expect(err).NotTo(HaveOccurred())` in Ginkgo.
- **Both positive and negative cert validation:** SPIRE tests both valid chains AND invalid chains (wrong CA, expired certs). Apply the same rigor to our bundle/SVID tests.
- **Suite-based integration organization:** Each feature gets its own integration suite with config, execution steps, and teardown — mirroring our `Context()` organization in Ginkgo.
